Here's an example of a user registration function in PHP:

**Note:** This code does not include any error handling or database connection, please make sure to add these features according to your needs.

```php
<?php

function registerUser($username, $email, $password) {
    // Define the database connection settings
    $servername = "localhost";
    $usernameDB = "your_username";
    $passwordDB = "your_password";
    $dbname = "your_database";

    // Create a new connection to the database
    $conn = new mysqli($servername, $usernameDB, $passwordDB, $dbname);

    // Check if the connection was successful
    if ($conn->connect_error) {
        die("Connection failed: " . $conn->connect_error);
    }

    // Hash the password
    $hashedPassword = hash('sha256', $password);

    // Prepare the SQL query to insert new user data into the database
    $sql = "INSERT INTO users (username, email, password) VALUES (?, ?, ?)";

    // Execute the prepared statement with parameters
    if ($stmt = $conn->prepare($sql)) {
        $stmt->bind_param("sss", $username, $email, $hashedPassword);
        $stmt->execute();

        // Check if the user was successfully registered
        if ($stmt->affected_rows == 1) {
            return true;
        } else {
            echo "Error: User not registered. Please try again.";
            return false;
        }
    }

    // Close the prepared statement and connection
    $stmt->close();
    $conn->close();

    // Return false if there was an error registering the user
    return false;
}

?>
```

You can use this function to register new users by calling it with their username, email address, and password:

```php
$username = "new_user";
$email = "newuser@example.com";
$password = "mysecretpassword";

if (registerUser($username, $email, $password)) {
    echo "User registered successfully!";
} else {
    echo "Error registering user. Please try again.";
}
```

**Important Security Note:** Never store passwords in plain text in your database! Always hash them using a secure algorithm like `hash('sha256')`. Also, make sure to use prepared statements with parameters to prevent SQL injection attacks.

**Database Setup:**

To make this code work, you need to set up a database table named "users" with the following columns:

```sql
CREATE TABLE users (
    id INT AUTO_INCREMENT,
    username VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL,
    email VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL,
    password VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL,
    PRIMARY KEY (id)
);
```

Remember to replace `your_username`, `your_password`, and `your_database` with your actual database credentials.

